\begin_layout Plain Layout
used: In some multicellular organisms, cell size can influence organ and
 organism size.
 This scaling is absolute in Caenorhabditis elegans, in which the cell number
 is fixed and perturbations to cell size result in proportional changes
 in organ and organism size (Irle and Schierenberg 2002; Cook and Tyers
 2007; Watanabe et al.
 2007).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Homeo:
\series default
 However, in a large number of species, such as the tiger salamander, alteration
s to cell size can be compensated for by changes in cell number to preserve
 organ size (Fig.
 1) (Fankhauser 1945).
 In addition, forcing proliferation in fly wing imaginal discs alters cell
 size, but triggers sufficient apoptosis to maintain organ size (Neufeld
 et al.
 1998).We refer the reader to Roth andWalkowiak (2015) and Penzo-Me´ndez
 and Stanger (2015) for further discussion of organ size regulation.
\end_layout

